Perimeter Defense - Email Security > [T1]: DMARC Record Creation

DMARC Record Creation

Multiple tools can help us create DMARC records for our domains, such as the Dmarcian free tool. It takes you through a wizard to answer a set of predefined questions and generates a DMARC record based on your answers.

 

Figure - zoom in

 

If its the first time your organization implements DMARC, its vital to take extra caution because a single mistake may cause havoc and interrupt business operations. For a smooth deployment, a gradual push of DMARC is highly recommended.

 

The very first thing to do is to start in monitor mode. We cant use a quarantine policy or reject before we know all our sending servers. This may look like an easy task since mail servers are well known. However, its always surprising to find out how many legit servers are sending emails from your domain you are unaware of, such as marketing emails sent by third parties and alerts from your servers/administrative tools. No matter how neat your assets inventory is, you will discover a couple of sending mail servers you did not know about.

 

To start monitoring and collecting all sending servers, we only need to create a DMARC record with the policy set to none and publish it in the DNS server. This is a risk-free step that organizations can take to move forward with DMARC implementation.

 

v=DMARC1; p=none; rua=mailto:dmarc-inbox@yourdomain.com

 

We often call this "Everyone first DMARC record" because every organization has to start with. Once published, we will start receiving aggregated reports. The problem with these reports is that we have to sift through an XML file to extract meaningful information, such as legit sending mail servers' IP addresses. A typical aggregated report looks like this:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

Figure - zoom in

 

This was a report Google sent to inform cyberdefenders.org that the Google mail server received three messages from the @cyberdefenders.org domain. The sending server IP address was 209.85.220.41, and the three messages passed both DKIM and SPF verification.
 

Organizations can build in-house tools or use open source ones such as parse-dmarc to parse DMARC XML reports and present them in a digestible format. There are also commercial services such as Dmarcian and UriPorts. In that case, organizations set aggregated reports destination (rua=) to an inbox owned by the service provider. This instructs receiving servers to send these reports to the service provider to parse them automatically. The receiving server/report generators will have to verify that the service provider is waiting for your reports to come by querying the DMARC record at <your-company.com>._report._dmarc.<service-provider.com>

For example, Facebook uses a service provider called PhishLabs to parse its DMARC reports.

 

Figure - zoom in

After monitoring the situation for two to three months, analyzing reports, and collecting a list of all legitimate sending mail servers for your domain, the next step is to ensure that all IPs are included in the SPF record and DKIM is appropriately configured. Ensuring that messages sent from legit mail servers have SPF and DKIM aligned is crucial.

 

The next step is gradually moving from monitor mode to active mode and taking action against failed messages. This means changing the policy from none to quarantine and applying that to a small portion of the mail traffic using the (pct=) tag.

 

 v=DMARC1; p=quarantine; rua=mailto:dmarc-inbox@yourdomain.com; pct=10;

 

The 10% percent can be increased over time till 100% is reached. Please note that the absence of (pct=) tag from the DMARC record means applying the policy to all traffic. So, removing the (pct=) tag and using (pct=100) will have the same result. 

 

The final step is to move slowly from quarantine to reject using the help of the (pct=) tag. A REJECT DMARC policy provides the highest protection against email spoofing.

 

Here is a diagram showing how DMARC verification works end-to-end:

 

Figure - zoom in

 

  • omar@sender-company.com sends an email to oways@receiving-company.com.
  • Mail.sending-company.com receives the message and transfers it to mail.receiving-company.com.
  • Mail.receiving-company.com receives the message.
  • If DMARC verification is turned off on mail.receiving-company.com, no action will be taken, and the message will be delivered to oways@receiving-company.com.
  • If DMARC verification is turned on; mail.receving-company.com verifies DMARC and queries dns.sender-company.com for DMARC policy:
    • None: take no action against failed messages and deliver them to the destination inbox.
    • Quarantine: treat failed messages as suspicious and place them in junk/spam.
    • Reject: drop the message.

 

At the end of this section, I hope you have realized how critical is DMARC for organizations' security and how big organizations such as cisco.com and nsa.gov find it very challenging to implement a DMARC REJECT policy.
